@NODE "Mail_313" " Re: Requesters "
From: Jesper Svennevid <jesper@fxrealm.com>
Date: 06-28-99 13:27:42
Subject: @{b}Re: Requesters@{ub}

From: "Jesper Svennevid" <jesper@fxrealm.com>


> From: "David McMinn" <D.Mcminn@eee.rgu.ac.uk>
> 
> > A bit more system-friendly way would be to (atleast for accessing
> > devices), would be to search for the device within the doslists
> > (FindDosEntry() is available for just these occations :D)
> 
> I don't know what FindDosEntry is used for, but I don't know what 
> that has to do with the question of turning off requesters that
> come up for your program. Say you booted without a startup-seuqeunce
> and ran a program that tried to open the file ENV:myprog.prefs.
> Normally you'd get a requester saying "Please insert volume ENV: in
> any drive" but if you set your windowptr to be -1 that won't 
> happen.

That's exactly what I meant, you can use FindDosEntry() (you must lock
the doslist before you can search tho' ;) to see if 'ENV' is available
(as an assign or whatever), and if it isn't, check for 'ENVARC' (you
can't be THAT sure that ENVARC: is available, even though it 'should'
be.), and act accordingly to the results. I've put this into action
in util/cdity/availmem2.lha, and although the source for that program
is in assembly, it's commented rather ok(it was a while since I wrote
it :D) so it shouldn't be that hard to figure out how to write a
similar routine... (AvailMem2/src/AvailMem2_settings.s, the routine
is _FindDevice)

A quick port of the routine would be something like this:

int FindDevice(char* deviceName)
{
   APTR dos_list; // this is SURELY some other type :P

   // lock doslist

   dos_list = LockDosList(LDF_ALL|LDF_READ);

   // try to locate the device matching name

   dos_list = FindDosEntry(dos_list,deviceName,LDF_ALL);

   // unlock doslist

   UnLockDosList(dos_list,LDF_ALL|LDF_READ);

   if(0L != dos_list)
      return TRUE;
   return FALSE;
}

Then you could do like this:

   // save in ENV if available

   if(FALSE != FindDevice("ENV"))
   {
      SaveConfig("ENV:MyConfig.cfg");
   }

   // save in ENVARC if available

   if(FALSE != FindDevice("ENVARC"))
   {
      SaveConfig("ENVARC:MyConfig.cfg");
   }

This code would save the configs only if the devices in
question were available, and you would still have the
more important requesters available(like i/o-errors,
and stuff like that) ...

-----------------------------------------------------------
