@NODE "Mail_319" " Re: Shells "
From: Stephen Williams <sw@nysa.u-net.com>
Date: 06-03-99 19:12:26
Subject: @{b}Re: Shells@{ub}

From: Stephen Williams <sw@nysa.u-net.com>

Mike Carter <mike.carter@bigfoot.com> wrote:
> I'd like to sprout a new shell process from within my program for the
> user to play with.
> 
> What is the best way to achieve this, maybe not the easiest, but
> 'correct' way?

Have a look at the autodocs for dos.library's Execute() function.
It can spawn shell processes, and might well do what you want.

> And how can I force it to work from a specific directory path - not
> necessarily the same as where the program creating the shell started
> from?

Urp, good question.  Try changing directory before spawning the new
process.  I think processes inherit their current directory from
their parent.  The easiest way to change directory is by using the
non-ANSI but still fairly common chdir() function.  If your C library
doesn't have it, I have the source for a C library and can send it
to you.

-Stephen



