@NODE "Mail_321" " Re: Shells "
From: Stephen Williams <sw@nysa.u-net.com>
Date: 06-09-99 22:18:48
Subject: @{b}Re: Shells@{ub}

From: Stephen Williams <sw@nysa.u-net.com>

Mike Carter <mike.carter@bigfoot.com> wrote:
> I didn't know about chdir().  Will give it a try - I use SAS-C.  I did
> try ChangeDir() from dos.library and another command very similar too.

SetCurrentDirName(), probably.

> But they just trashed the directory the the command was originally
> called from and did nothing to the spawned shell :(

Don't forget, a program run from the shell is run almost as if it's a
function called from the shell process - the shell LoadSeg()s the code
and jumps to it using RunCommand().  Any changes made to the current
directory will therefore affect the shell that they were run from.
Old versions of AmigaOS (1.x) had "cd" as a C: directory command, not
as a shell builtin, and it worked by exploiting this feature.

If you use CurrentDir(), _always_ change back to the directory you
started off in before exiting.  chdir() does this for you; the version
I have installs an exit handler using atexit() to change the directory
back just before the program exits.

-Stephen (waiting for Olaf to correct all the mistakes in the above ;-)



