@NODE "Mail_326" " Re: Shells was: Re: Q: Debugging "
From: Ben Hutchings <womble@zzumbouk.demon.co.uk>
Date: 06-29-99 02:32:19
Subject: @{b}Re: Shells was: Re: Q: Debugging@{ub}

From: Ben Hutchings <womble@zzumbouk.demon.co.uk>

On Sun, Jun 27, 1999 at 09:17:50PM -0400, Voytek Laniewski wrote:
> From: Voytek Laniewski <voytek@cyburban.com>
> 
> Hello Tim
> 
> On 25-Jun-99, Tim Hanson wrote:
> > From: Tim Hanson <msinister@connectfree.co.uk>
> > 
> > Voytek Laniewski wrote this on 25-Jun-99 at 20:17:30
> > Hi Voytek 
> > 
> > -> Hi
> > -> Can anybody recommend a debugging setup? I have an 060 so I use
> > MungFriend
> > 
> >    I`m sure everybody has an opinion on this. I like mungwall and have
> > just got Cyberguard to replace enforcer. I use newsushi to send output to
> > a kingconsole.
> 
> Speaking of which... I replaced CON: and RAW: with their KingCON
> equivalents. What I noticed though was that I got a small but continuous
> memory leak. After doing an avail it would show that some memory
> disppeared. It did not happen if I switched back to the original shell.
<snip>

Please don't confuse shells with console handlers.  Their functions
are a bit messed up on the Amiga, in that the console handler
implements a history and complex editing functions while the shell and
other interactive programs generally read complete lines.  However,
the boundary between them is very well-defined.

KingCON and ViNCed are alternative console handlers (the standard one
is called con-handler and is of course part of Kickstart).  They
display windows, instantiate console units within those windows, and
implement a stream (file) interface to those console units.

ZShell, csh, pdksh, etc are alternative shells.  They read commands,
load and run programs, execute scripts, and so on.  They normally
use a console handler for their input and output.

