@NODE "Mail_333" " Re: Spreadsheet MUI "
From: Jarno van der Linden <jarno@kcbbs.gen.nz>
Date: 06-01-99 22:21:32
Subject: @{b}Re: Spreadsheet MUI@{ub}

From: Jarno van der Linden <jarno@kcbbs.gen.nz>

> From: "Mike Carter" <mike.carter@bigfoot.com>
> 
> How does Micro$lop Excel (and TurboCalc I suppose) mange a spreadsheet
> as they seem to be of a humungous size in both X and Y directions!

I started a spreadsheet program many years ago. I got as far as having
a working data structure and a simple interface before I moved to more
interesting things.

The data structure I used was based on interlinked lists. Let's see
if I can remember this correctly...
Each non-empty cell is stored as a node, with pointers to the next non-empty
cell above, below, left, and to the right of it. This way I can store
a sparse spreadsheet reasonably compact even though it may span thousands of
rows and columns.
To get faster access to a random cell, I keep a list containing pointers
to the first non-empty cell (i.e. node) in each non-empty column. A similar
list for the first node in each non-empty row is also kept.
A random cell is then found by searching the column list for the desired
column number, and then following the nodes down until we find the node
with the desired row number. You can also use the row list first, and then
scan across the nodes if that involves less nodes.

That's how I did it back then anyway. I now realise using a hashing function
would be a better way to go.

I would like to see a spreadsheet.mcc. It amazes me that MUI hasn't been
utilised for these sort of things a lot more, like is done with dll's.

---JvdL---

