@NODE "Mail_336" " Re: Spreadsheet MUI "
From: Jarno van der Linden <jarno@kcbbs.gen.nz>
Date: 06-03-99 02:34:13
Subject: @{b}Re: Spreadsheet MUI@{ub}

From: Jarno van der Linden <jarno@kcbbs.gen.nz>

> From: Linus McCabe <sparkle@hehe.com>
> 
> Could you explain what hashing is?

You could pick up any book on algorithms, but here is a starter:

The problem that hashing is trying to solve is the fast lookup of
data based on a key. In case of a spreadsheet, the data would be whatever
is inside the node (or a pointer to it), and the key would be the row/column
index.

A hashing function maps the key to an array index. It does this by some
simple mathematical formula, not by a search. Using this index, you
look in an array and retreive the data at that array index.
An example of a really stupid hashing function for a spreadsheet is to
use something like RowIndex + ColumnIndex*(MaxRowIndex+1) which is your
basic 2D array indexing formula. This is the really obvious way of storing
a spreadsheet.

But wait! If the shreadsheet can be of a size up to 2^16 by 2^16, that would
need an array of 2^32 items, which requires a bit more memory than your
average Amiga.

Hashing gets around that by allowing multiple keys (and hence data items)
to map to the same index. For example, the hashing function could simply
be to take the RowIndex as an index into an array of 2^16 entries. (If
you want to have an even larger range of rows in your spreassheet, you
could use RowIndex % 65536 for example).

But wait! What do I do if two non-empty cells map to the same place in the
array?

This is what is called a collision. Collisions can be resolved by keeping
a list of data at an array index, rather than one data item.

To add data, you use the hashing function on the data's key to obtain an
array index. You use this index to look in the array, and add your data
with key to the list stored at that position.
To retrieve data, you again use the hashing function on the data's key
to obtain an array index. You then hunt down the list at that array
position until you find the key (and hence the data) you're after.

To speed up the scan through the list, you should keep it in sorted order
so that you know when it's pointless to look any further if the data isn't
there.

Using the RowIndex as a hashing function is actually not a good idea, as
all the cells in a row will map to the same index, while a row with no
non-empty cells will result in a totally unused array index, which is
just a waste of space. Maybe a better one would be
(RowIndex + ColumnIndex) % 65535.

The art of hashing is to devise a key, hashing function, and array size for
your problem domain (i.e. spreadsheets) which minimizes the number of
collisions while remaining within your memory budget and speed requirements.

---JvdL---

