@NODE "Mail_352" " AW: [amiga-c] Still serial device troubles "
From: Fritsch Alexander <Alexander.Fritsch@icn.siemens.de>
Date: 06-22-99 09:11:32
Subject: @{b}AW: [amiga-c] Still serial device troubles@{ub}

From: Fritsch Alexander <Alexander.Fritsch@icn.siemens.de>

> On 22-Jun-99, Jonas Hulten wrote:
> -snip-
> 
> int main(void)
> {
>   dprintf("Program started.");
> 
>   if (OpenMidiIn())
>   {
>     while (1)
>     {
>       ULONG signals;
>       signals = SIGBREAKF_CTRL_C;
> 
>       ReceiveMidiData(&signals);               /*   Hmmmmmmmmmmmm- trouble
> */
> 
>       if (signals & SIGBREAKF_CTRL_C)
>         break;
>     }
>     CloseMidiIn();
>   }
> 
>   dprintf("Program ended.");
>   return 0;
> }
> 
> 
> 
> Passing the address of an auto variable -   Oops  (:o)  !!!
> 
> you should make it STATIC or declare  it globally.....
> 
> ----------------------------------------------------
> Colin Wenzel. Australia.   colstv@hotkey.net.au
> 
    Passing the address of an automatic variable is absolutely legal in
this case. There is no need for static. As long as you are inside the scope
of the function which declares the local variable the stack of this function
remains alive and so you can pass the adress of this local variables.

    Good Example
    ---------------------


    void function2(*int a)
    {
     /* do something */
    }

    void function1 (void)
    {
     int a;

    function2 (&a);

                                    /* <----a is alive up to here */
    }






    Bad Example
    -------------------

    int * function1(void)
    {
     int a;
     a=5;
     return (&a);
                                  /* <---- a dies here */ 
    }

    void function2(void)
    {
     int *b;

     b=function1();        /* so here we use the address of a dead (no
longer existing) variable. That is wrong.
    }

    Kind regards Alexander Fritsch

