@NODE "Mail_354" " Re: Still serial device troubles "
From: Ben Hutchings <womble@zzumbouk.demon.co.uk>
Date: 06-22-99 23:45:12
Subject: @{b}Re: Still serial device troubles@{ub}

From: Ben Hutchings <womble@zzumbouk.demon.co.uk>

On Mon, Jun 21, 1999 at 10:38:20PM +0200, Jonas Hulten wrote:
> Den 20-Jun-99, skrev Ben Hutchings:
> 
> >>           si->serialio->io_Baud = 31250;
> >>           si->serialio->io_ReadLen = 8;
> >>           si->serialio->io_WriteLen = 8;
> >>           si->serialio->io_StopBits = 1;
> >>           si->serialio->io_SerFlags = SERF_XDISABLED | SERF_RAD_BOOGIE;
> >>           si->serialio->IOSer.io_Command = SDCMD_SETPARAMS;
> 
> > You need to set io_RBufLen as well, and you may need to set
> > io_CtlChar.  You are leaving io_RBufLen equal to 0, which is invalid.
> > You should also use |= and &= to set and clear bits in io_SerFlags, so
> > that you preserve the current settings.
> 
> The examples in the RKM doesn't set io_RBufLen. Well, I tried it and it
> didn't change anything.
<snip>

I noticed that you didn't enable any handshaking, either.  Does MIDI
not use handshaking?

I couldn't see any error in your code; it looks much the same as my
working code.

In case you want to compare, here is the code from my dialler.  This
is not an example of good code; this is a fairly quick hack that I
have tested and do not want to fiddle with.

Because it's for a dialler, it waits for serial, timer and break
signals.  It uses a moving window on the serial stream in which the
script processor searches for various strings.

...
#define SERIAL_BUF_LENGTH       256
...
static char SerBuf [SERIAL_BUF_LENGTH];
/* these variables define the current 'window' within the serial buffer */
static char *WinStart = SerBuf, *WinEnd = SerBuf;
...

enum DialError ReadSerial (void)
{
    int ser_len;

    ULONG wait_flags = (1 << TimePort->mp_SigBit)
                     | (1 << SerPort->mp_SigBit)
                     | SIGBREAKF_CTRL_C,
          recv_flags;

    /* if the window is nearly the whole buffer, drop the first few bytes */
    if (WinEnd - WinStart >= SERIAL_BUF_LENGTH - 8)
        WinStart += 8;

    if (WinStart != WinEnd)
        memmove (SerBuf, WinStart, WinEnd - WinStart);
    WinEnd   = SerBuf + (WinEnd - WinStart);
    WinStart = SerBuf;

    /* fill the buffer some more */
    SerReq->IOSer.io_Command = SDCMD_QUERY;
    DoIO ((struct IORequest *)SerReq);
    ser_len                  = (SerReq->IOSer.io_Actual == 0) ? 1 :
                               ((WinEnd + SerReq->IOSer.io_Actual
                                 <= SerBuf + SERIAL_BUF_LENGTH - 1) ?
                                 SerReq->IOSer.io_Actual :
                                 SerBuf + SERIAL_BUF_LENGTH - 1 - WinEnd);
    SerReq->IOSer.io_Command = CMD_READ;
    SerReq->IOSer.io_Length  = ser_len;
    SerReq->IOSer.io_Data    = WinEnd;

    /* bastard flags don't seem to get cleared when I expect :-( */
    SetSignal (0, wait_flags);
    SendIO ((struct IORequest *)SerReq);

    recv_flags = Wait (wait_flags);

    if (recv_flags & SIGBREAKF_CTRL_C)
        return DERR_BREAK;

    if (!(recv_flags & (1 << SerPort->mp_SigBit)))
    {
        AbortIO ((struct IORequest *)SerReq);
        WaitIO ((struct IORequest *)SerReq);
        return DERR_TIMEOUT;
    }
    GetMsg (SerPort);

    /* echo received data */
    Write (StdOut, WinEnd, ser_len);

    WinEnd += ser_len;
    *WinEnd = 0;

    return DERR_NONE;
}

-----------------------------------------------------------
Ben Hutchings - womble@zzumbouk.demon.co.uk, http://www.zzumbouk.demon.co.uk
