@NODE "Mail_369" " sub-structure dereferencing "
From: ROBERT MEYERS <meyersrl@songs.sce.com>
Date: 06-22-99 17:13:41
Subject: @{b}sub-structure dereferencing@{ub}

From: "ROBERT MEYERS"<meyersrl@songs.sce.com>

All, I have an interesting (to me anyway) problem.

I am defining a structure which contains another 
sub-structure, but the catch is that the sub-structure 
is already defined by the hardware documentation and 
does not contain any fields for allowing linkage to a 
larger enclosing structure.  The sub-structure cannot 
be modified and still maintain compatibility with the 
hardware.  The hardware operates on the data in the 
sub-structure using DMA, periodically the hardware 
informs the upper software layer that the work on the 
current sub-structure is complete and that it may be 
removed or other housekeeping to be done.

The problem is how do I know which enclosing structure 
the sub-structure which was processed belongs to?

There will potentially be MANY of these enclosing 
structures in the final executable.  And I will need to 
do some processing on other data in the structure 
depending on the what happens with the sub-structure 
processing.

example:

struct BabyStruct  */ DMA'able by hardware */
{
volatile ULONG *DataArea;
volatile ULONG Flags;
volatile ULONG StatusRegister;
volatile UBYTE Modifier;
}


struct DaddyStruct
{
    struct Node linkage;
    LONG somethingcritical;
    LONG somethingbad;
    LONG sonethingworse;

    struct BabyStruct baby;

} dad;

Hardware passes the address of the sub-structure that it 
was working on up to the software for housekeeping.

I had some thoughts along the lines of comparing 
addresses while walking through the Nodes in the List 
that will hold the enclosing structure. e.g.,

for(/* Node referencing code here*/)
/* search though Nodes list */
{
    if(&(dad.baby) == unknown_baby_struct)
    {
      /* Addresses match, dad is enclosing struct */
    }
   else
    {
      /* Addresses don't match, try again
    }
/* not sure of the syntax here, but you get the thought*/
}

Any ideas?

Bob


