@NODE "Mail_373" " Re: sub-structure dereferencing "
From: Ben Hutchings <womble@zzumbouk.demon.co.uk>
Date: 06-24-99 22:25:15
Subject: @{b}Re: sub-structure dereferencing@{ub}

From: Ben Hutchings <womble@zzumbouk.demon.co.uk>

On Tue, Jun 22, 1999 at 04:13:41PM +0000, ROBERT MEYERS wrote:
<snip>
> struct DaddyStruct
> {
>     struct Node linkage;
>     LONG somethingcritical;
>     LONG somethingbad;
>     LONG sonethingworse;
> 
>     struct BabyStruct baby;
> 
> } dad;
> 
> Hardware passes the address of the sub-structure that it 
> was working on up to the software for housekeeping.
<snip>

As long as all the BabyStructs are in DaddyStructs, you can do:

    pdaddy = (struct DaddyStruct *)
        ((char *)pbaby - offsetof( struct DaddyStruct, baby ));

This sort of long-winded expression really makes me want to stuff C
and use assembler. ;-)

I think offsetof is defined in stdlib.h.

