@NODE "Mail_379" " Re: Text file lines "
From: Ben Hutchings <womble@zzumbouk.demon.co.uk>
Date: 06-24-99 22:36:25
Subject: @{b}Re: Text file lines@{ub}

From: Ben Hutchings <womble@zzumbouk.demon.co.uk>

On Wed, Jun 23, 1999 at 01:50:14AM +0200, Christian Hattemer wrote:
> From: Christian Hattemer <Chris@mail.riednet.wh.tu-darmstadt.de>
> 
> On 23-Jun-99 Mike Carter wrote:
> 
> > What do people suggest to be the easiest way to read a line of text
> > (upto the NEWLINE \n character) into a string buffer using *only*
> > amiga run-time libraries?
> 
> > FGets includes the NEWLINE so is not good.  But FGetC needs a loop so
> 
> Why not remove the \n then?
> 
> Readbuffer[strlen(Readbuffer) - 1] = '\0';

Don't do that - the last line might not have a newline at the end of
it.  Get a pointer to the end of the string, and then check whether
there's a newline there or not.

The problem with FGets, and fgets, and so on is that they require you
to specify how long a line you are prepared to handle.  I don't really
like setting arbitrary limits like that. :-(

-----------------------------------------------------------
