@NODE "Mail_385" " Re: Text file lines "
From: Ben Hutchings <womble@zzumbouk.demon.co.uk>
Date: 06-28-99 00:17:05
Subject: @{b}Re: Text file lines@{ub}

From: Ben Hutchings <womble@zzumbouk.demon.co.uk>

On Sun, Jun 27, 1999 at 04:55:42PM +0200, Christian Hattemer wrote:
> From: Christian Hattemer <Chris@mail.riednet.wh.tu-darmstadt.de>
> 
> On 24-Jun-99 Ben Hutchings wrote:
> 
> >>> FGets includes the NEWLINE so is not good.  But FGetC needs a loop so
> >> 
> >> Why not remove the \n then?
> >> 
> >> Readbuffer[strlen(Readbuffer) - 1] = '\0';
> 
> > Don't do that - the last line might not have a newline at the end of
> > it.  Get a pointer to the end of the string, and then check whether
> > there's a newline there or not.
> 
> This is a good Point, but on the other hand this check takes extra time,
> especially when a Function Call like strchr() is involved.

Since you're calling strlen anyway, you already know how long the
string is.  If the length is greater than 0 (it should always be, but
I suppose you should check for this error condition) then test whether
the last character is '\n'.  If so then change it to 0.

> I don't think it's a Problem to do this without check in my Program because
> it's a working on a Configfile written by itself. The \n also in the last
> Line, unless its removed in an Editor...

If you use a text file, then you should assume that it may be edited
in a text editor.

-----------------------------------------------------------
Ben Hutchings - womble@zzumbouk.demon.co.uk, http://www.zzumbouk.demon.co.uk
Team *AMIGA* | Jay Miner Society | Linux - the choice of a GNU generation
It is easier to change the specification to fit the program than vice versa.

