@NODE "Mail_402" " Re: troubleshooting help "
From: Rod Schnell <rodsch@telusplanet.net>
Date: 06-14-99 00:26:57
Subject: @{b}Re: troubleshooting help@{ub}

From:    Rod Schnell <rodsch@telusplanet.net>

Hello jack

On 13-Jun-99, jack york wrote:
> From: jack york <jyork@voyager.net>
> 
> Hello,
> 
> I have a program that creates a process to handle the printing.  The 
> child process can be sent any number of different reports to print.  No
> matter which report I send, the program always fails like this:

I see you call UnlockPubScreen(NULL, scr); immediately after opening the
window. You should retain the lock until you're finished using the screen,
all windows are closed and there's no chance of another one opening.

> Now, if I elimiate opening the window ( CA_OpenWindow ), everything
> works fine.  I can run as many reports as I want and the program never 
> fails.  I have tried removing the ClassAct code and just opening a 
> standard intuition window and it still fails.  When I create the process
> I have NP_StackSize, 100000.  It was only 8000 but I thought this might
> be a stack problem and wanted to elimate that posibility.

Doesn't sound like a stack problem, and I doubt the lock would cause this. I'd
say an invalid pointer somewhere else is most likely. On the other hand, the
child's screen pointer would be invalid if the parent closes it while the
child
is running and if it happens that the screen closes before openwindow, it
would
certainly crash the child.

> I don't use AllocMem anywhere in the program (parent or child) so the
> above failure seems to be a failure in the graphics module.  Or am I
> making the module fail somehow?  How can I tell, if possible, what the
> offset (4284 from above) into the graphics module points to?  Does 
> anyone have any suggestions as to how I go about finding this problem?
> I have tried everything I can think of.

There is a program called FindHit, that's supposed to find what line in your
code is causing the hit. Don't ask me how to use it, I don't use FindHit
myself. I usually debug stuff like this by commenting out suspect parts of
the code and putting printf() and Delay() in and around the faulty code until
I find it.

  Rod


