@NODE "Mail_407" " Re: variable args "
From: Ben Hutchings <womble@zzumbouk.demon.co.uk>
Date: 06-28-99 00:36:47
Subject: @{b}Re: variable args@{ub}

From: Ben Hutchings <womble@zzumbouk.demon.co.uk>

On Mon, Jun 28, 1999 at 12:01:25AM +0100, Duncan Strand wrote:
> From: Duncan Strand <dstrand@zebs.screaming.net>
> 
> 
> I'm trying to write a function that does the same as sprintf, but
> allocates memory for the resulting string.

That will be extremely difficult to do.  If you're going to stick
to just DICE, it might be a good idea to copy and modify the code
for sprintf (if that's allowed).

> So I could call the function like "str = newstr( "Cows %s %d times",
> "moo", 3 );" and the string would contain "Cows moo 3 times"
> 
> I've looked through dices documenation and cannot find any reference to
> variable argument functions.

Look in a book which describes ANSI C then!

>         va_start( va, fmt );
>         sprintf( dest, fmt, va );
>         va_end( va );
<snip>

How do you expect this to work?  sprintf requires you to pass all
the arguments again, and you don't know what the arguments are.

You have to use something like:
    vsprintf( dest, fmt &va_arg( va, int );

I'm not convinced that that is portable, though.

-----------------------------------------------------------
Ben Hutchings - womble@zzumbouk.demon.co.uk, http://www.zzumbouk.demon.co.uk
Team *AMIGA* | Jay Miner Society | Linux - the choice of a GNU generation
It is easier to change the specification to fit the program than vice versa.

