@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_417" " Re: Won't compile - why? "
From: Volker Barthelmann <volker@vb.franken.de>
Date: 06-16-99 01:37:00
Subject: @{b}Re: Won't compile - why?@{ub}

From: Volker Barthelmann <volker@vb.franken.de>



On Tue, 15 Jun 1999, Chris Pratt wrote:

>     I'm currently working my way through a book on learning C, and one of
> the programs in the book won't compile with vbcc.
>     The program:
> 
> #include <stdio.h>
> 
> int radius, area
> 
> main()
> {
>     printf( "Enter radius (i.e. 10): " );
>     scanf( "%d", &radius );
>     area = (int) (3.14159 * radius * radius);
>     printf( "\n\nArea = %d\n", area );
>     return 0;
> }
> 
>     Now, I can see what the (albeit simple) program should do, but when I
> try to compile it (from wibble.c to wibble) using vbcc, I get these errors:
> 
> t_9_0.o: In "_main":
> Error 21: t_9_0.o ((CODE+0x26): Undefined reference to__ieeefltsld.
> Error 21: t_9_0.o ((CODE+0x5e): Undefined reference to__ieeefltsld.
> Error 21: t_9_0.o ((CODE+0x48): Undefined reference to__ieeemuld.
> Error 21: t_9_0.o ((CODE+0x7c): Undefined reference to__ieeemuld.
> Error 21: t_9_0.o ((CODE+0x96): Undefined reference to__ieeefixds.
> vlink failed returncode 20
> vlink -s -x -dn vlibm68k:startup.o "T:t_9_0.o"  -lvc -lamiga -o wibble
> failed

To save space vbcc does not link in floating point support by default.
You have to specify a math library, e.g. -lmieee. See the docs for
further details.

Volker


