@NODE "Mail_420" " Re: WorkBench startup problems "
From: Ben Hutchings <womble@zzumbouk.demon.co.uk>
Date: 06-05-99 03:11:26
Subject: @{b}Re: WorkBench startup problems@{ub}

From: Ben Hutchings <womble@zzumbouk.demon.co.uk>

On Thu, Jun 03, 1999 at 10:03:13AM +0100, Tim Hanson wrote:
> From: Tim Hanson <msinister@connectfree.co.uk>
> 
> Tim Hanson was stunned to discover that it was 02-Jun-99 and could not resist
> writting about [amiga-c] WorkBench startup problems after all it was
> Wednesday.
> 
>       Watcha Tim
> 
>  This is what you wrote:

Do you think you could reduce the length of this attribution?  It's
amusing the first few times...

<snip> 
>     He`s loosing the plot and talking to himself. Thought i`d reply to my own
> mail and berate myself publically. The problem was stack overflow. It /was/
> my *inept programming.* Does anyone know why this didn`t show up when run
> from CLI? Still let this be a lesson to us all (or something).

You probably set a large stack size in your CLI to cope with all those
GNU ports that eat stack like crazy.

My opinion is that relying on the user to set stack size in the CLI
setting or WB icon is immensely stupid, and the program's startup code
should allocate a new larger stack if necessary.  Unfortunately not
many people like to touch their startup code.  I suppose the best
thing to do is to be very sparing with stack space.

-----------------------------------------------------------
Ben Hutchings - womble@zzumbouk.demon.co.uk, http://nowhere.at.the.moment
