@NODE "Mail_424" " Re: WorkBench startup problems "
From: Ben Hutchings <womble@zzumbouk.demon.co.uk>
Date: 06-12-99 02:33:13
Subject: @{b}Re: WorkBench startup problems@{ub}

From: Ben Hutchings <womble@zzumbouk.demon.co.uk>

On Wed, Jun 09, 1999 at 11:48:54AM +0100, Tim Hanson wrote:
> From: Tim Hanson <msinister@connectfree.co.uk>
> 
> Ben Hutchings wrote this on 09-Jun-99 at 01:14:06
<snip>
> -> I wrote my own startup code for DICE which allowed me to make small
> -> Amiga-specific programs.  It had a large number of optional features
> -> so that it could be customised to the needs of each program.  I have
> -> yet to do the same for gcc; libnix seems to have fairly good minimal
> -> startup code anyway.
> 
>     Does startup code have to be written in assembler?

Only a very little.  Setting up the data pointer for a small-data
program requires you to use assembler.

> I`d quite like to have a go at this but have no idea where to
> start. I`m using DICE. Any pointers?

Since I wrote mine for DICE (version 2) you could have a copy of that.
I haven't used it in a while, and it will probably need adjustment to
work with version 3.

There is one bug in it that I know of, and that is that it does not
call auto-initialisation and auto-exit code.  If you make a resident-
able program (one which duplicates its static data at startup) then
any references to static data in static data (e.g. static char ch,
* pch = &ch;) generate auto-initialisation code that relocates them
after duplication.  This means that such references will not work
correctly if you use this startup code.  I simply avoided using such
references, but you will probably want to fix this bug.

-----------------------------------------------------------
Ben Hutchings - womble@zzumbouk.demon.co.uk, http://nowhere.at.the.moment
Team *AMIGA* | Jay Miner Society | Linux - the choice of a GNU generation
